         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
           <p> Valentinian, Valens and Gratian were emperors together from 364 to 375</p>
            <p>It is possible to reconstruct part of the opening formula (i) and identify fragments from the title of the responsible official (ii) from the description of the work executed (iii).</p>
            <p>ii: the governor's name ended -sios. The <foreign xml:lang="la">praeses</foreign> who apparently honoured the same emperors in <ref type="inscription" n="P.119">P.119</ref> had a name ending -ius. 
               He, however, is described as <foreign xml:lang="la">v(ir) p(erfectissimus)</foreign>, not, as here, <foreign xml:lang="la">clarissimus</foreign>. This may indicate several interventions during the reign, 
               under different governors, to be associated with other evidence for a major rebuilding in this street in the late fourth to fifth century in 
                <ref type="inscription" n="P.122">P.122</ref>, <ref type="inscription" n="P.136">P.136</ref> and <ref type="inscription" n="P.137">P.137</ref>, 
               very probably to repair damage caused by the earthquake of 364 <!-- , see Introduction XXX --></p>
         </div>
         
